The difference of kubernetes and openshift is that kubernetes has replicaset, whereas openshift has replica controller.
1. Replicaset supports set-based selector requirements; replica controller supports equity-based selector requirements.
2. in OpenShift you can swap out container images inside of manifest or deployment config for upgrade or change it up etc.; whereas in a deployment which uses replicaset, rolling update is needed.
Replica controller is not recommended...



ImageStreams: 
it's just an extra layer between application and image in OpenShift, in yaml file instead of 'image: quay.io/company/myapp:v1', you can use an ImageStreamTag 'myapp:latest'
without an ImageStream:
Deployment
     ↓
Container Image
(quay.io/company/myapp:v1)

with an ImageStream:
Registry
     ↓
ImageStream
     ↓
Deployment

ImageStream updates deployments with tags
1. tracks updates in image registry (say, in quay.io/company/myapp@sha256:abc123... the 'sha256:...' part) 
2. triggers image changes in deployments

ImageStream workflow:

New image pushed
        ↓
ImageStream updated
        ↓
Deployment automatically rolls out
        ↓
     New Pods



