buildConfig: 
the whole purose of having build config is to automate the process of building container images from either source code or another image
1. create a buildConfig by adding a yaml file in OpenShift
2. run $ oc new-app <app-link-in-github> in terminal
it would show that buildconfig.build.openshift.io "blabla" created in the output, that's how to create a build config manually
actually when create an application, a build config will be auto-created

then start a build in terminal:
$ oc start-build <build-config-name>
alternatively start a build in OpenShift UI:
click the build config, select 'start build' in the ellipsis, after it's finished, the created image can be found in 'output to' in Details


Build configuration stratefy:
there are 4 strategies to create the build configuration:
1. source to image: a tool to create a docker-formatted container image, then injects source code into it
2. pipeline: defined in Jenkinsfile, and manged via OpenShift
3. docker
4. custom: define a custom builder image which is a plain docker-formatted container image embedded with build process logic

Build input:
git -> dockerfile -> binary -> image -> input secrets -> external artifacts (not recommanded)

buildah: a tool that builds container images


